  <!-- ============ H2 #12: PRE-CTA CLOSING STORY ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="margin-bottom: var(--s-6);">
        <div class="eyebrow">12 &middot; What "right door first" looks like</div>
        <h2>Yacht surveyor mortgage, structured right.</h2>
        <p>SAMS AMS yacht surveyor, 12-year practice in South Florida, dual-discipline Y&amp;SC plus H&amp;M. Schedule C showed $94K net &mdash; but the practice had $22K of depreciation, $8K of home office deduction, and a $14K equipment Section 179 in the prior year. Two lenders looked at the $94K AGI and declined the file as insufficient income for the $920K Fort Lauderdale waterfront he wanted. We pulled the Form 4562 and Form 8829 detail, ran the Fannie Mae Form 1084 cash flow analysis with depreciation and Section 179 addbacks, and computed qualifying income at $137K. Approved at $920K. Closed in 33 days. The right loan program existed the whole time &mdash; the first two lenders just didn&rsquo;t know how to read a self-employed marine professional file.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="pre-cta-photo">
        <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/7578899/pexels-photo-7578899.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800" alt="House keys at closing" width="1400" height="700" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1400x700/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Yacht+Surveyor+Closings';">
        <div class="pre-cta-photo-caption">
          <span class="label">33-day close &middot; Fort Lauderdale, FL</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

